After Thomas de Ebberston was removed from his bailiwick and office he never appointed a woodward, received any bark‚ or enjoyed any other profits or liberties in the township except as a commoner. This they are ready to prove. Therefore they say that neither Robert Wyerne and Thomas Thurnef nor their ancestors or feoffors ever had the right to elect a woodward, or to take bark or oak in the township from Robert de Scarborough and Thomas White‚ or their ancestors or feoffors, except at the good will of the commoners and tenants. They say that the allowance of the claim will prejudice the King and his heirs in case the Earl should happen to die without issue, and also prejudices the Earl and the other commoners and tenantS.
